Blind Landing
o
W. J. Charnley
(Superintendent, Blind Landing Experimental Unit)
A description is given of the basic principles and method of operation of a singlechannel automatic blind landing system developed by the Blind Landing Experimental Unit. The system uses the internationally accepted radio aid ILS for approach guidance to the point where more accurate information is required and then two new guidance elements, magnetic leader cable and radio altimeter, are introduced for the final landing. One of the great advantages of the system is its flexibility and if new guidance elements are developed the system will be easily adapted.
Extensive flight tests have been made in all weathers and the performance achieved is much better than that obtained in manual landings in good visibility.
In considering the application of the system to civil aviation the outstanding problem is that of safety and reliability. Various suggestions are discussed briefly and the possible requirement for an independent pictorial monitor is mentioned. Early thoughts on a monitoring system are described.
i. INTRODUCTION. The limiting weather conditions in which an attempt may be made to land an aircraft are dictated largely by considerations of safety. When fog, low cloud, heavy rain or snow prevail and the weather deteriorates beneath permitted limits the present high level of safety of civil transport operation is maintained by a diversion of the aircraft to an alternative airport with the consequent reduction in operating regularity. A recent paper presented to the Institution of Electrical Engineers1 summarizes various radio and electronic approach aids which are currently available, and indeed are in regular airline use, which permit safe instrument approaches to be made in bad weather to heights of about 200 ft. in visibilities as low as ^oo yd., the final landing being completed manually by the pilot after having made visual contact with the ground. If the cloud base is lower than 200 ft. or the visibility less

