than £00 yd. the pilot is unable to see the runway approach lighting pattern sufficiently well to obtain enough information to complete the landing with safety and he is forced to overshoot for a second attempt or divert to another airport where the weather is more favourable. Alternatively, of course, the instruction to divert is communicated to the aircraft long before it reaches the intended destination, or the service is suspended altogether.
With the above limits, representative of modern practice, it is estimated that about 4 per cent of all landings scheduled by our main airlines are diverted due to bad weather. This not only dislocates the airline service, causing inconvenience and irritation to passengers and confusion in the traffic pattern and in air traffic control, but also represents ,a serious loss of revenue to the operator.
As the speed at which an aircraft approaches the runway increases, and unfortunately this is the tendency with modern aircraft, the existing standards of safety may only be maintained by raising the operating limits and hence reducing regularity still further. Also, as the traffic density increases over the next ten years it will become increasingly important to maintain more precise timekeeping in the terminal area and missed approaches resulting in a second attempt to land will have to be reduced to a minimum. The case, therefore, for being able to land at an intended destination irrespective of weather conditions is overwhelming and, looking even further ahead, the economic operation of a supersonic transport aircraft may well depend upon its ability to land at its destination safely, on time, and at the first attempt.
It can be shown by experiment and also from experience 1 that in making a manual landing following an instrument approach in very low visibility there is not the slightest margin for error on the part of the pilot and that our present-day limits barely allow sufficient time to complete the manual landing. In other words there is little hope of extending with safety a system of instrument approach aid plus manual/ visual landing to minima much worse than 1 $o ft. cloud base and joo yd. visibility. Hence to permit routine operation in worse weather, that is zero or near zero visibility, it is necessary to eliminate the final visual phase completely.
For some time now the Blind Landing Experimental Unit of the Royal Aircraft Establishment has been actively engaged upon research and development into various methods of achieving this objective of making a completely blind landing, but only recently has it been possible to release details of some of the work. The object of this paper is to outline one or two of the systems. The intention is not to discuss the reasons for the systems chosen but to describe the results achieved and their application to civil aviation.
The first method to be described is in an advanced stage of development and consists of landing the aircraft automatically by coupling it through an automatic pilot in the aircraft to a radio guidance system, the pilot

