system. The landing starts with an automatic approach (ABC) in which signals proportional to the vertical and horizontal displacements of the aircraft from the beam of the internationally accepted radio approach aid called Instrument Landing System (ILS) are fed to the automatic pilot to lock the aircraft to the radio beam. Automatic approach is already in use in civil aviation and is one of the aids, mentioned already, which permit accurate approaches to be made to a height of about i^o ft. to 200 ft. above the ground. Now, despite its name and for reasons which are described later in this section, ILS is, in its present form, an approach aid only; in general it cannot be used for guidance at heights below i oo ft. which would permit the aircraft to complete the landing under automatic control. Two new and more accurate guidance elements, the magnetic leader cable in the horizontal plane (CDEF), and radio altimeter in the vertical plane (EFG), are, therefore, introduced during the ,last mile. Just before touch-down any drift due to crosswind is removed (FG) so that the aircraft lands accurately aligned with the runway. After touch-down the pilot disengages the automatic pilot and steers the aircraft to a stop, using signals from the magnetic leader cable displayed on his flight instruments (GH). A final feature is the inclusion of automatic speed control in which the engine throttles are moved automatically to maintain a constant speed during the approach (BCDE) and then are throttled back to reduce the speed during the landing (EFG).
One of the great advantages of the system is its flexibility and in this respect it is superior to any other system under development. It uses the internationally accepted radio approach aid to the point where more accurate guidance is necessary and only at this stage introduces new elements into the system. Should future development improve the ILS approach guidance to such an extent that it can be used for landing guidance as well, the system will be easily adapted. This is a very promising line of development.
It will be noted that the complete system makes use of the following items of equipment:

(i) Instrument landing system (ILS) for azimuth and glide-path approach guidance.
(ii) Magnetic leader cable for azimuth landing guidance, (iii) Radio altimeter for vertical landing guidance, (iv) Automatic pilot for automatic coupling to the radio guidance
elements. (v) Automatic speed control. (vi) Flight director instrument display for the presentation of pilot
monitoring information.

