In the present context the most important difference between the British military equipment and that in current use on some civil airfields lies in the use of a simple parabolic aerial to restrict the localiser radiation to the forward looking sector including the approach path. The beam-width of the combined space pattern is about ±20 degrees to half power points (Fig. 2). This reduces site errors and beam distortions, improves the approach accuracy and increases the number of sites on which an automatic approach can safely be made into the takeover zone of the leader cable for the automatic landing phase. As will be shown later, narrowing the beam further to about ± 10 degrees by more aerial development could possibly remove completely the need for leader cable for azimuth guidance during landing.
2. Azimuth landing guidance. The ILS localiser may provide inadequate azimuth guidance during the landing phase because:

(a) The zero may not be aligned accurately enough with the runway centre-line. For instance in a typical installation, because the information is angular in character, i degree change in beam centre-line (within the specified tolerance) produces a lateral displacement of centre-line in the touch-down area of $o to 60 ft.
(b) Due to site errors there may be bends in the beam that are too large to accept.
(c) In some installations the beam may be offset from the runway heading and therefore be unacceptable for landing.

To overcome these deficiencies a magnetic leader-cable system has been developed providing very accurate azimuth guidance (± $ ft.). The information is linear in character and hence the accuracy is independent of range. The ground equipment consists of two cables laid one either side of the runway at a distance of 2^0 ft. from the centre-line and extending from about 5000 ft. beyond the runway threshold in the undershoot area to as far down the runway as azimuth guidance is required. The cables are fed from alternators supplying a different frequency to each cable and fitted with an electronic control to stabilize and equalize the current (4 amp.) in each cable.
The principle of operation is shown in Fig. 3 (a). At any point between the two cables the difference in the magnetic fields due to the current in them is a measure of the horizontal distance of the point from the runway centre-line. Hence an airborne receiver, frequency discriminating between the two fields, can produce a signal proportional to the lateral distance of the receiving aerial from the runway centre-line. At a fixed height the sensitivity (Fig. 3 (b) ) is almost constant within the coverage of die cables, but as height is increased the sensitivity falls.
The airborne equipment used to date (Fig. 4) consists of a rotating loop aerial and a simple three-valve receiver whose output is low level d.c. current similar to that of the ILS receivers. The quality of the

