3. Vertical landing guidance. The ILS glide path cannot be used for vertical guidance on to the runway for two main reasons:
(a) The glide-path beam is inclined at a fixed angle to the ground and hence for an aircraft landing at a constant or nearly constant airspeed on the glide path there is very little, if any, reduction in the rate of descent at touch-down.
(b) The present ILS glide path in general cannot be relied upon for a smooth signal on all sites below a height of about 100 ft.
Hence, as in the azimuth plane, it is necessary to change the approach guidance in the vertical plane.
A very convenient and simple method of checking the rate of descent and making a flare-out on to the runway is to arrange for the flight path of the aircraft to follow an exponential curve starting from the glide path. To do this, it is necessary to reduce the aircraft rate of descent in proportion to the height above the runway and this can be achieved by means of a control law of the form, 0D:=/i + A(c//i/d£), where 8D is the

