6. Instrument display. Pilot monitoring of the satisfactory progress of the automatic landing is of great importance to the safety of the manoeuvre and to the peace of mind of the pilot. It will be shown in Section £ that the extent of the monitoring required in a system fully acceptable to civil aviation with all the necessary safeguards is not yet resolved; so far the system has been developed with monitoring information provided on the aircraft instruments. With minor modification the display used for monitoring automatic approach can be used for monitoring automatic landing so that at all stages of the approach and landing the pilot is presented with continuous information on the same instruments.
Four small indicators mounted close to the instrument display show the progress of the landing as it passes through the phases CD, DE, EF and FG of Fig. i, and form an essential part of the safety system. The automatic height switching circuits are so arranged that the switching to one phase primes only the next phase. This ensures that the phases are only switched one at a time and in the correct sequence. An extra APPROACH/LAND switch is necessary to enable the pilot to select either automatic approach only or full automatic landing. Various interlocks are provided on this switch to increase safety.
3. AUTOMATIC LANDING. In Section 2 a very brief outline was given of the basic system and in the following paragraphs the various components were described. It is now worth examining the system again from a functional point of view.
An automatic landing is always preceded by an automatic ILS approach with automatic control of airspeed. The procedure for approach is similar to that used with the standard autopilot, i.e. manual selection of the aircraft configuration followed by manual engagement of the autopilot. If an automatic landing is desired, however, LAND is manually selected soon after the start of the glide, preferably at a height between 600 and 1000 ft. and from then on the sequence switching of the various phases of the landing system is automatic. Selection of LAND also automatically switches the radio altimeter from the high to the low range if this has not already been done by the pilot. Failure to switch to LAND results in the aircraft making a normal automatic ILS approach only with no automatic switching to the landing phases.
At a height of about 300 ft. (Fig. 1) when the aircraft enters the coverage of the leader-cable system, a signal from the leader-cable automatic gain control primes the sequence switching circuit and changes the azimuth control from ILS localiser to leader cable (point C). The sensitivity of the ILS glide-path signal into the autopilot may also be reduced at this point. At approximately 100 ft. (point D) the ILS glide-path signal into the autopilot is disconnected and the aircraft is controlled to a pitch attitude datum that was established whilst the aircraft was flown down the glide path (Section 2). This continues down to a height of about 60 ft. when the flare-out, computed from the radio altimeter height information commences (point E). Also at a

