The rate of descent at touch-down and the distance of the point of impact along the runway are, of course, related since if the chosen vertical velocity is small, giving a very smooth landing, the flight path at touchdown is almost tangential to the runway so that small disturbances due to variations in wind gradient or turbulence near the ground give a large change in touch-down point. If the average vertical velocity is increased the flight path at touch-down is obviously steeper and disturbances have less effect upon the touch-down point. As mentioned in Section 2, the control of throttle during this period is also most important and only by closely linking the closing of the throttles to the flare-out manoeuvre will the longitudinal scatter along the runway be reduced to a minimum.
In earlier tests the touch-down velocity aimed at was less than 1 ft/sec. and the r.m.s. value of the scatter was 160 yd., about a point 270 yd. further along the runway than the origin of the ILS glide path. In the tests quoted above, the touch-down velocity was increased to a mean of 2 ft/sec, a more usual figure, and the r.m.s. of the point of impact was reduced to 6s yd. about a point only 1 $o yd. from the glide path origin. In other words, 68 per cent of all landings occurred within a distance of 130 yd.
It is worth comparing these results with those obtained from the manual landing of a similar jet aircraft in good visibility using the same approach speed (ii$ knots). In this case 68 per cent of all landings occurred within a distance of 300 yd.—more than double the scatter obtained with the automatic system. In a larger jet aircraft the figure increased to almost 400 yd., an increase which would not be expected with the automatic system. It is fair to claim, therefore, that not only will the automatic system land the aircraft when the weather prevents the human pilot, it also performs the operation much more precisely.
5. PROBLEMS IN CIVIL APPLICATION. Having described briefly the performance obtained with an experimental automatic landing system, it is now worth considering some of the problems to be faced in a civil version of the equipment. The outstanding one is that of safety. The present civil accident rate from all causes is about two in 106flyinghours, and this figure must be at least maintained and if possible reduced. It seems reasonable to suggest, that in order to maintain this figure from all causes, the reliability of any particular system should be an order of magnitude higher. On this argument, an automatic landing equipment should have a failure rate of not worse than one in io7 flying hours. With a reliability of this order, the extra landing safety obtained from the use of the system can produce a significant improvement in the overall accident rate since statistics show that about 30 per cent of the total accidents occur during approach and landing. Furthermore, as has been mentioned already, improved regularity could be relied upon and economic gain obtained.
Quite clearly such a stringent safety requirement must be fed into the automatic landing system right from the start. It demands new techniques

