in design, new standards of quality control of components, in assembly, in testing and in engineering approach to the system. But, in addition to questions of detailed design, it poses very important questions upon the general philosophy to be adopted in the design. The arguments advanced include those which follow.
At one extreme is the suggestion that only a single channel is necessary. Since the landing phase only lasts for about two minutes and since each piece of airborne equipment can be tested for correct operation before it is switched automatically into the system, it is argued that by careful design and monitoring a single channel will give the reliability required. This is the argument that has been used so far in the flight trials of the experimental equipment and with very careful maintenance of both autopilot and radio equipment an acceptable safety level has been achieved. In the opinion of the author it is unlikely that any certificating authority will accept any type of single-channel system for civil use.
Another argument demands multiple channels of the same equipment so arranged that if one channel fails another takes over automatically and completes the landing without any change of flight path. This school of thought maintains that the chances of any pilot preventing disaster following certain malfunctions at a low height, say $o to 60 ft., would be very small indeed and consequently they do not admit that the pilot can play any part in the automatic landing operation (even in an emergency) until after touch-down. Opinion on the number of channels required varies between two and four. FearnsideS and Majendie6 discuss this problem broadly, provide figures on the failure rates of particular automatic equipment and suggest a design philosophy.
Yet a third argument again favours multiple channels but demands that the channels be independent, i.e. an automatic landing system should be backed up by a completely independent pictorial monitor so that the pilot has at all times 'the feel' of the landing, and so that in the event of a failure of the automatic system he can take over immediately and make a manual landing from the picture. It is recognized that the automatic landing system should be the primary system because it relieves the pilot of load and ensures better touch-down accuracy, but it is claimed that a manual system should be available in an emergency. A variation of this argument is that such an independent monitor would be very useful during the introductory period of automatic landing (say for 5 years) until user confidence in the automatic system had been built up. This is, however, not very convincing' since during the confidence-building phase the automatic system need only be used in good visibility or visual take-over conditions. One possible system for producing the independent picture is the 'televiewer' discussed later in Section 6.
A discussion of the factors which influence the philosophy, the choice of number of channels, the additional safety obtained by adding extra channels of the same and different systems and the relative reliability of radio and autopilot equipment could very easily form the basis of a

