The ground equipment also must not be forgotten. It too must match up to this same reliability and although it should be easier to achieve on the ground the standard required in the air, yet the ground equipment must be available over very long periods and not just during a flight. This requires attention equal to that given to the airborne equipment.
To add automatic landing as an extra facility to an existing autopilot is likely to prove difficult unless provision has already been made for the required level of safety in the earlier design but it is suggested that when the design of the automatic control system for a future aircraft is considered in detail the inclusion of automatic landing as part of that system may not prove to be a prohibitive price to pay for the operational advantage of an all-weather landing facility. In this connection it is most encouraging to note that both B.E.A. and B.O.A.C. in their new aircraft to be built in this country have stated a requirement for the automatic control system to include automatic flare-out, i.e. automatic control to touch-down in the vertical plane with provision for full automatic landing at a later date. The automatic flare-out using radio altimeter as guidance will increase the safety level at the present weather limits and may also lower the limits. It will improve the consistency of landings in marginal conditions and at the same time provide valuable experience on the operation of an automatic control system at low height. It is a very significant step towards the completely automatic system in both vertical and lateral planes, the adoption of which must depend to some extent upon international agreement on the lateral guidance system. B.E.A. and B.O.A.C. are the first civil operators to take this step.

Guidance. Two of the problems that arise concern the guidance elements of the basic system; the installation of leader cable and the improvement of the ILS glide path. Dealing first with the leader cable, its advantages are that both the ground and the airborne equipment are simple, and the lateral performance, as was shown in Section 4, very accurate. Its disadvantage is the difficulty of installing the cable on the ground and this will now be discussed.
The basic auto-landing system requires leader-cable azimuth guidance from a range equivalent to an aircraft height of 300 ft., i.e. 6000 ft. in length from the glide path origin or about 2000 ft. beyond the full Calvert approach lighting pattern. On many sites, this would require the purchase of extra ground and, in some cases, would encroach into builtup areas. Despite the fact that the cable may be buried, laid on the surface or even mounted on poles, there is nevertheless a case for attempting to shorten the leader cable to not longer than the end of the lighting pattern. To achieve this means improving the accuracy of the

