I 3 I

ILS localiser guidance by a factor of two. The question thus arises as to whether it would not be better to improve the ILS localiser so that the leader cable might be dispensed with altogether. The necessary improvement could be introduced on most sites by narrowing the localiser beam to about 10 degrees and using a beam control system equivalent to that used in the British military system. In such a scheme, an in-line localiser would, of course, be mandatory.
The possible mutual interference between leader cable and other lighting cables, power lines, telephone cables, &c, must also be considered. Quite apart from any unwanted signals induced in these other cables by the leader cables, it is known that other cables distort the leader-cable field pattern although, so far, their effects upon control have never been serious. Investigations of these problems have been made and methods of overcoming them are straightforward though in some cases troublesome to apply.
Turning now to the glide path, it will be remembered from Section 2 that there is a phase in the present system lasting about 3 sec. between 100 ft. and 60 ft. where because of possible uncertainties in ILS glide-path information, the aircraft is flown by attitude control only on an open loop system. A new design of aerial should soon be available to civil aviation which on a good site makes the glide path acceptable for automatic control down to ^o ft. If this could be repeated on all sites the 'open-loop' phase could be eliminated and a further reduction in the spread of touch-down point along the runway achieved.
There is thus the possibility that with an improved ILS system both in azimuth and elevation, the leader cable and the 'open-loop' phase may be dispensed with. Installation of ground equipment would be eased (no leader cable) and it would not be necessary to adopt a completely new guidance system. On the other hand there is always the possibility that even an improved ILS system might be unacceptable at some sites and civil operators may be tempted to consider a completely new guidance system for approach and landing.
6. 'TELEVIEWER.' It has for many years been felt very desirable to present to the pilot in bad visibility a picture in the cockpit similar to the one he would see during a night landing in good visibility. If this could be done, it was felt that perhaps the pilot could make a manual landing using this picture. This would provide a manual blind landing system (i.e. the pilot still in the loop) in contrast to the automatic landing system (pilot outside the loop but monitoring) so far discussed. In Section g mention was made of the possibility of introducing an independent manual blind landing system in order to achieve the required overall reliability. One such independent system is the 'televiewer', the broad principles of which are now discussed.
Flight experiments have been conducted by B.L.E.U. initially using various types of visual masks and more recently using a closed-circuit television system installed first in a Devon and later in a Meteor aircraft.

