A photograph of the Devon installation is shown in Fig. 9. The television camera is mounted on the nose of the aircraft and the monitor tube is viewed by the pilot. The experiments, made both by day and night, have shown that a pilot can land an aircraft satisfactorily with an approach speed of 13 £ knots using a picture of runway lights presented to him on a cathode-ray tube, and that this speed is not limiting if the picture is of reasonable quality. They have also established the limits acceptable to the pilot, of some of the parameters of the picture.
As one example of the type of experiment made, Fig. 10 shows two photographs of the cathode-ray tube viewed by the pilot to obtain the information required to land the aircraft. The tests were made at night and a simple lighting pattern was used to outline the runway and provide the necessary visual guidance. The picture displayed to the pilot has been deliberately degraded to represent the quality likely to be obtained from possible types of 'televiewer' systems in bad weather. The upper picture represents a static resolution of 10 minutes of arc whilst the lower picture represents £0' resolution. Normal visual resolution is about 1', so that the picture represents definitions about 10 and £0 times worse than is possible with the naked eye. Using 10' resolution a large selection of pilots experienced no difficulty in landing at a speed of 13 s knots, but with a resolution of §0' satisfactory landings at this speed were not possible. In this way it was possible to determine the resolution required from the 'televiewer' system.
The concept of the 'televiewer' is then as follows. A number of radio beacons are placed in some suitable pattern about the runway, and the aircraft carries a receiver capable of direction finding on each beacon, thereby generating in the aircraft a picture of these beacons on a cathoderay tube. The position of the beacons is measured relative to the aircraft axis, thus giving a picture similar to that seen by the eye through the cockpit windscreen. None of the aircraft's normal flight instruments are used in generating it. Since neither visible light nor infra-red will penetrate fog (as distinct from haze) a radio frequency must be used.
The concept is simple enough, but the difficulty lies in finding an airborne receiver that has at the same time the simplicity and the accuracy of direction finding likely to be required by the civil user. There are many possible types of system, but the number has been narrowed down by theoretical work at B.L.E.U. Experimental work has begun on the more promising ones, but it will be a year or two before it is known whether any of them has an acceptable performance combined with promise of engineering into an acceptable system. Should a feasible system emerge it will be considerably longer before a fully engineered version is available.
