£ on safety apply equally to this system, and the question of independent monitoring is similarly relevant. One ground equipment can handle only one aircraft at a time and hence the landing rate obtainable from one equipment is restricted to about one aircraft every two minutes. Also the ground computer may have to be reset to the characteristics of different aircraft. Nevertheless the success achieved so far is another indication of the need for civil aviation as a whole to consider seriously and in detail its requirements for automatic landing.
8. CONCLUSIONS. An automatic blind landing system has been described which has been extensively flight tested in all weathers. One of its great advantages is its flexibility and should future development produce improved guidance elements the system will be easily adapted. The landing performance of the experimental equipment is better than that achieved in manual landing in good weather.
Detailed consideration is being given to its application to civil aviation. A brief analysis shows that:

(a) On the airborne side the outstanding problem is that of achieving the necessary level of safety acceptable for routine civil use. Careful study of design philosophy as well as detailed engineering is necessary but it is suggested that when the design of the automatic control system for a future aircraft is considered, the inclusion of automatic landing as part of that system may not prove to be a prohibitive price to pay for the operational advantage of an all-weather landing facility.
, (£>) With regard to ground installations, the major problems of civil application could be reduced appreciably and probably removed completely if further development of the ILS approach guidance system for landing is possible.
(c) A completely independent monitor for automatic landing may be required. A system for producing a pictorial display in bad weather is in the early research stage.

