DISCUSSION
D. O. FRASER (English Electric Co. Ltd.): It has been most interesting to listen to Mr. Charnley's magnificent review of this development and to have it described—one might almost say at last—in public. I remember seeing the initial version of this system demonstrated at Martlesham about eight or nine years ago, which shows how much development is required to bring a system such as this to a stage where you can begin to think about placing operational requirements.
• It is also encouraging that B.O.A.C. and B.E.A. have decided to go ahead and install the necessary equipment at least to get operational experience of this system. It may be that the only way in which confidence can be built up sufficiently to accept automatic landings will be from operational use of the equipment in good weather conditions: seeing what happens again and again. The philosophy of automatic landing was dealt with by Mr. Charnley very well and the question of acceptance is a very difficult one, because it is not quite enough to quote a given level of safety as a criterion. I have discovered this myself because I have frequently spoken at Institute meetings on the question of air traffic control over the North Atlantic, where we have a complicated and cumbersome system which, beyond about one or two hundred miles from the shore, only attempts to eliminate a collision risk which is of a much lower order than the general risk of aircraft accidents from other causes. But the statistical argument alone does not convince people because they tend to focus on the possibility of collision, no matter how remote, and consider all the possibilities of a miss irrelevant! I think the problem regarding blind landing is made more difficult by the fact that here pilots have more individual control over the situation. If you demonstrate that the proportion of landing accidents is higher without the automatic system, the pilot is not necessarily convinced by that argument; he assumes it is others that make statistics so bad, not him. As with crossing the road, one knows that the chance of being knocked down has a certain statistical probability, but we none of us take that as applying to ourselves.
I would like to ask Mr. Charnley about the directional ILS localiser. I understand that for some time there has been a directional localiser at the C.A.A. technical development centre at Indianapolis which uses a waveguide two

