hundred feet long, and is capable of giving an accuracy in azimuth of about one eightieth degree. I would be interested to know whether anybody here has any more information on this.
My second question is on the general case for automatic landing. It would be valuable to know whether a study has been made of the cost to airlines of not being able to land due to weather. The direct cost, covering only the proportion of days on which one cannot land without such aid is very small, but the fact is that one always has to carry a contingency reserve of fuel because one might not be able to land at destination. I think that if one reached a stage of reliability of automatic landing systems where one could eliminate this reserve of fuel, and only carried that needed for air traffic control delays, it might lead to a significant improvement in the economics of airline operation—particularly considering turbine aircraft. As I recall it the Comet I used to land regularly at London Airport with the order of two hours' fuel reserve, which was getting on for the same weight as its total payload. If one can eliminate reserves of this order it might increase the effective payload of jet aircraft by something like fifty per cent. A second point is the question of reliability of schedules. If you can depend upon aircraft arriving at their destinations, you can then plan your schedules accordingly, to make maximum utilization of your fleet. One of the great troubles in civil aviation is that because of delay in one part of an airline system you have repercussions all over the system, delaying other connecting services, &c. and this disruption can take many hours to put right, resulting in seat cancellations and irritation of passengers.
Mr. CHARNLEY: I agree completely with Mr. Fraser that the necessary confidence will only come through actual use of the equipment. The introduction of the system must be made in good weather, by an accumulation of experience, when with the equipment working the pilot can actually see visually that things are going well and that the system is performing satisfactorily.
Often in discussion the point is made in favour of the televiewer type of monitoring display that it would be very valuable during the introduction of the automatic landing system because it produces a picture of the runway and would inspire confidence. In fact we see the necessary confidence coming from the use of the system in good weather. The steps that are now being taken towards using automatic flare will go far in the direction of building confidence.
Mr. Fraser asked for information on the ILS aerial work at Indianapolis. This work is still going on and the figure quoted for the stability of the beam centreline is about one-eightieth of a degree or one minute of arc. It was very encouraging to discuss these problems with the C.A.A. experts from Indianapolis at a recent I.A.T.A. meeting and find that they too were fairly optimistic about obtaining the accuracy required for landing from the present approach-guidance system. This development looks quite promising.
Captain LINCOLN LEE (B.O.A.C.): The fact that this system is dependent on ILS means that it may take pilots some time to get experience of and confidence in it. ILS installations are notoriously unreliable, due to many causes; and people on eastern routes may find London the only place where they can trustingly make use of it. Admittedly London is the place they most need it.
Mr. CHARNLEY: ILS is not a particularly complicated radio guidance system, and could be made more reliable. This is one of the reasons we favour basing a system around, say, ILS, rather than a more complicated equipment like the Bell Auto Landing System, which, after all, uses a narrow beam lock-follow radar.

