The second point was that of displaying runway edge lights and stub-bars with no approach pattern. This is quite deliberate, because in any radio system which we can see ourselves designing, in very bad weather we may be limited in range. And the information we are really after is landing information as distinct from approach information. The main problem then is to provide sufficient information for the flare, or the final approach and flare starting from a height of, say, two hundred feet. Originally we had approach lights which were presented on the screen, but in more recent work we have been concentrating on the final flare. Obviously (and I now come to the Chairman's point) we are trying to reduce to a minimum the number of ground beacons that might be required. This involves a detailed study of the work done by Calvert in connection with ordinary visual aids. There is a very delicate optimum between the minimum amount of information that is required (and may be essential from a safety point of view), and the number of ground sources which might form a practical layout. A point to be remembered here is that the great deficiency in visual guidance is in the vertical plane. A display with stub-bars will give adequate roll guidance but the problem is in the vertical plane. And one of the problems there is trying to assess from pictures, such as those shown on the screen, the aiming point or any deviation from glide-path. Given the televiewer type of display, the aiming point might be computed and superimposed upon the runway picture, so that the pilot can see the point to which he is going. All that we have done so far is produce a display on which experiments can be made. We have always appreciated that the precise form which the display might have to take in an eventual solution may have additional computed information with it.
